    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The timing for sanding is crucial, or you'll end up with a messier situation than a goblin raid on a poorly guarded treasure pile! You absolutely cannot sand the mud when it's still damp, or you'll just smear the wet goop around like a startled, mud-covered goblin.\n\nThe key is to wait until the mud is completely *hard*—not just dry on the surface, but rock solid all the way through. If you press on it and it feels tacky or squishy, it's not ready. You want it to feel as firm as a well-packed goblin's sack of stolen shiny trinkets.\n\nA good trick is to let it dry for the time specified by your joint compound manufacturer, but if you're impatient, you can gently tap the area with a light hammer or a piece of scrap wood. If it sounds dull and solid, it's ready for a light sanding. If it sounds hollow or soft, give it more time.\n\nWhen you do sand, use a fine-grit sandpaper (150-180 grit is usually good for the final smoothing). Sand *gently* and *lightly*—you are just smoothing the high",
      "source": "target",
